# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bill-watkins-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The **1884 Indianapolis Hoosiers** baseball team finished with a 29–78 record, 12th place in the American Association.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] This was the only season the team was in operation.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The **1884 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1884.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American Association's regular seasons ended on October 15, with the Providence Grays and New York Metropolitans as the NL and AA pennant winners, respectively.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The newly founded Union Association regular season ended on October 19, with the St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the AA and NL began with Game 1 of the first World's Championship Series (the first inter-league championship game of its kind in the Major Leagues) on October 23 and ended with Game 3 on October 25, in what was a best-of-five-playoff.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Grays swept the Metropolitans in three games, capturing their first World's Championship Series.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the 1884 season, in September 1883, the Union Association was formed, in direct contravention to the reserve rule (that a ballplayer could be reserved by a team) of the 1883 National Agreement (a.k.a.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Tripartite Agreement) signed between the National League, American Association, and minor league Northwestern League.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] In response to formation of the UA, the AA expanded their league from an eight teams to twelve teams to undermine the weak footing the UA had, as UA teams were mostly in cities that already had established AA and NL teams.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The latter played their last game on August 2, and were replaced by the minor league Eastern League's Richmond Virginians to finish Washington's schedule.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Union Association was largely unstable throughout its only year in existence (though confidence in the league remained high), as three of its founding teams would not make it to the end of the season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Altoona Mountain Citys folded on May 31, and were replaced by the Kansas City Cowboys on June 7.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Keystones folded on August 7, and were replaced by the Eastern League's Wilmington Quicksteps.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Browns relocated to Pittsburgh as the Pittsburgh Stogies following their August 21 game.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Quicksteps would fold on September 15, while the Stogies would fold just three days later.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] On September 27, the Milwaukee Brewers and St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Paul Saints) were recruited from the Northwestern League to finish the Philadelphia / Wilmington and Chicago/Pittsburgh schedules, respectively.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 season featured the second African American player in the major leagues (following William Edward White five years prior), debuting May 1 and playing 42 games for the Toledo Blue Stockings of the American Association.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] During his tenure, he faced abuse from other players (including teammates), fans, and the press, and even threats of being mobbed by 75 men before a road trip to Richmond, Virginia, before being released due to injury on September 29, prior to the road trip.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] His brother Weldy Walker played on the Toledo Blue Stockings for five games between July and August, becoming the third African American in the major leagues.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 schedule consisted of 110 games for all teams in the American Association, which had twelve active teams, and 112 games for all teams in the National League and Union Association, each of which had eight active teams.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Each AA team was scheduled to play 10 games against the other eleven teams in their league, and each of NL & UA teams were scheduled to play 16 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League increased its total games per team from 98 to 112, 14 games to 16 games per seven opponents.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The new Union Association copied this format.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the American Association, expanding from eight to twelve teams, changed from the 98-game format to the 110-game format.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would continue to use their 112-game format through the following season, while the American Association would copy the NL format.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Union Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while American Association and National League Opening Days took place on May 1, featuring all twelve and all eight teams, respectively.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Union Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 19 featuring four teams, while the American Association and National League would see their final day of the regular season on October 15 featuring all twelve teams and four teams, respectively.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The 1884 World's Championship Series took place between October 23 and October 25.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Four teams played in four neutral or alternate sites in which they were treated as the home team.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] 35 tie games (19 in AA, 10 in NL, 6 in UA), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in *italics* indicates a team a player was on from a different league.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Any stat from said different league is not calculated to determine the league leader.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] Four of these teams folded, one of which relocated cities prior to folding.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1884-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Hoosiers hosted 11 Sunday games at the Bruce Grounds north of Indianapolis city limits in Center Township on May 18, 25, June 22, 29, July 6, 13, 20, August 3, 10, 31, and September 21.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-detroit-wolverines-season] The **1885 Detroit Wolverines** finished the season with a 41–67 record, finishing in sixth place in the National League.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The **1885 major league baseball season** began on April 18, 1885.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the Chicago White Stockings and the St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns as regular season champions of the National League and American Association, respectively.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the second World's Championship Series on October 14 and ended with Game 7 on October 24, in what was a best-of-seven-playoff.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The White Stockings and Browns ended the series in a disputed tie in seven games.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] This dispute was due to the Browns not considering their forfeit in Game 2 as a voided game, and as a result, claimed victory.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the 1885 season, the unstable single season Union Association disbanded.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Maroons of the Union Association joined the National League, in place of the disbanding Cleveland Blues.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The twelve-team American Association would contract down to eight teams, with the Columbus Buckeyes, Indianapolis Hoosiers, and Toledo Blue Stockings folding, while the late-entry Richmond Virginians returned to the Minor Leagues.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The National League's New York Gothams renamed as the New York Giants, and the American Association's Brooklyn Atlantics and Louisville Eclipse renamed as the Brooklyn Grays and Louisville Colonels, respectively.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The 1885 schedule consisted of 112 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place by the National League since the previous season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association, due to downsizing from a twelve-team league to an eight-team league over the off season, took on this format.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the final season for this format, as the AA would implement a 140-game format and the NL a 126-game format the following season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 18 featuring four teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 30, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 5 with a game between the Brooklyn Grays and Philadelphia Athletics, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 10, featuring four teams.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The 1885 World's Championship Series took place between October 14 and October 24, though was originally supposed to extend to October 31.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] Three teams hosted games at neutral sites, the Buffalo Bisons, Providence Grays, and St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] 4 tie games (1 in AA, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Beaneaters, Chicago White Stockings, and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1885-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings leave Lakefront Park (where they played for seven seasons) and move to West Side Park, where they would go on to play for seven seasons, partway through 1891.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-detroit-wolverines-season] The **1886 Detroit Wolverines** had the best winning percentage of any major league baseball team to play in Detroit.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-detroit-wolverines-season] They compiled a record of 87–36 for a .707 winning percentage.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-detroit-wolverines-season] Nevertheless, the Wolverines finished in second place, 2½ games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The **1886 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1886.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the third World's Championship Series on October 18 and ended with Game 6 on October 23, in what was a best-of-seven-playoff.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The Browns defeated the White Stockings, four games to two, capturing their first World's Championship Series.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Over the offseason, the National League's Buffalo Bisons transfer into the minor league International League and Providence Grays fold.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The two open spots are filled by the newly enfranchised Kansas City Cowboys and Washington Nationals.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The 1886 schedule consisted of 140 games for all American Association teams and 126 games for all National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Each AA team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams, while each NL team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other seven teams.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Both the AA's 140-game format and NL's 126-game format were newly-implementation for the 1886 season, each replacing the 112-game, 16 games against the other seven teams format that both leagues had from 1884 and 1885.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The NL would adopt the AA's format in 1888, and each league would use this 140-game format until 1892.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] American Association Opening Day took place on April 17 featuring six teams, while National League Opening Day took place on April 29, also featuring six teams.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The 1886 World's Championship Series took place between October 18 and October 23.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the Brooklyn Grays of the American Association (which was informally referred to as the "Beer & Whiskey League" due to its openness on alcohol, compared to the National League) to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] 28 tie games (13 in AA, 15 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1886-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Grays of the American Association begin hosting Sunday games, playing 14 games at Ridgewood Park in Ridgewood, New York on May 2, 16, 23, 30, June 6, 13, 20, July 18, 25, August 1, 22, 29, September 12 and 19.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The **1887 Detroit Wolverines season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The team won the 1887 National League pennant, then defeated the St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The season was the team's seventh since it entered the National League in 1881.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] It was the first World Series championship for the Detroit Wolverines and the City of Detroit.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] On March 13, after training in Macon, Georgia‚ the Wolverines began a six-week exhibition tour through the South and Midwest.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Catching duties were divided between **Charlie Ganzel** (51 games at catcher) and **Charlie Bennett** (45 games at catcher).
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Both were good defensive catchers, though neither hit particularly well.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Bennett had a better fielding percentage than Ganzel (.951 to .913), but Ganzel was stronger in range factor (6.78 to 5.64) and fielding runs (9 to 2).
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Bennett's career in baseball ended when he lost both his legs in a train accident.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] When the Detroit Tigers opened their new ballpark in 1896, they named it Bennett Park in his honor.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] It remained Bennett Park until 1912, when the newly built stadium on the same site was named Navin Field.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] First baseman **Dan Brouthers** was the first of four future Hall of Famers to play for the 1887 Wolverines.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Brouthers won five batting titles and seven slugging titles, and his career batting average of .342 is the 9th highest in major league history.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Brouthers was a key to the Wolverines offensive output in 1887 as he led the National League in runs (153), doubles (36), extra base hits (68), on-base percentage (.426), times on base (246), and OPS (.988).
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was also among the league leaders with a .338 batting average (3rd in the NL), .562 slugging percentage (2nd in the NL), 20 triples, 12 home runs (5th in the NL), 101 RBIs (4th in the NL), 71 walks (4th in the NL), and an at-bat-to-strikeout ratio of 55.6 (2nd in NL).
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The second baseman duties were split between **Fred Dunlap** and **Hardy Richardson**.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Dunlap played 65 games at second base but missed two months due to an injury.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] As a result, Richardson played 64 games at second base in addition to 58 games as the left fielder.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Richardson was a big contributor to the 1887 Wolverines, as he hit for a .327 average with 51 extra base hits, 131 runs scored, 178 hits and 94 RBIs.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Richardson was also a good fielder both at second base and in left field.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Third baseman **Deacon White** was also part of "The Big Four" acquired from Buffalo before the 1886 season, and is the second of four future Hall-of-Famers on the team.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] White won two batting crowns earlier in his career but was 39 years old in 1887.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He still hit for a .303 batting average and had 11 triples, 75 RBIs and 20 stolen bases.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] White was a nonsmoking, Bible-toting, church-going deacon.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] According to Lee Allen in *The National League Story* (1961), White was one of the last people to believe that the earth is flat.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Right fielder **Sam Thompson**, known as "Big Sam," was the third future Hall of Famer on the 1887 Detroit team.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Thompson was in his prime in 1887 and had a tremendous year.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was the National League batting champion with a .372 average, and he also led the league in slugging percentage (.571), hits (203), total bases (311), triples (23), RBIs (166), and runs created (127).
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] His 1887 total of 166 RBIs stood as a major league record for 40 years until Lou Gehrig broke it in 1927.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] 2 on the all-time home run list at the time of his retirement.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Center fielder **Ned Hanlon** was the fourth future Hall of Famer on the 1887 Detroit team.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Though inducted into the Hall of Fame based on his later performance as a manager, Hanlon was a good fielding center fielder who had tremendous speed and range.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1887, he stole 69 bases for the Wolverines.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He also hit .291 with seven stolen bases and 4 RBIs in the 1887 World Series.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The left fielder duties were split between second baseman/outfielder **Hardy Richardson**, and pitcher/outfielder **Larry Twitchell**.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In addition to pitching 15 games for the Wolverines, Twitchell played 44 games in left field and 9 games in center field.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Twitchell had a .333 batting average and collected 51 RBIs in just 264 at bats.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In his 15 games as a pitcher, Twitchell had a record of 11–1.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines' #1 pitcher in 1887 was **Charlie Getzien**.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Getzien had a record of 29–13 for the 1887 team.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Getzien started 42 games, pitched 41 complete games, and had an ERA of 3.73.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was among the league leaders in wins, win percentage (.690), inning pitched (366.2), and strikeouts (135).
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He was also first in the league with 24 home runs allowed.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In the 1887 World Series, Getzien had a record of 4–2 with a 2.48 ERA.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Baldwin played four seasons with the Wolverines.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1886, Baldwin had a record of 42–13 (the most wins ever by a Detroit pitcher) with a 2.24 ERA in 487 innings pitched, striking out 323 of 1936 batters faced.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Baldwin also completed 55 of 56 games, seven of which were shutouts.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1887, Baldwin's appearances were reduced from 56 games to 24, and from 487 innings to 211.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] He won only 13 games in the regular season for the 1887 Wolverines, but in World Series play, Baldwin pitched 5 complete games for a 4–1 record and a 1.50 ERA.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines' #3 pitcher was **George Edward "Stump" Weidman**.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Weidman led the National League with a 1.80 ERA for Detroit in 1881.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] In 1887, Weidman returned to the Wolverines, where he went 13–7.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] By late July, Weidman fell out of favor with manager William Watkins who considered Weidman to be a malcontent.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines sold Weidman to the New York Metropolitans on August 5, 1887.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines #4 pitcher was **Pete Conway**.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Despite his 8–9 record in 1887, Conway had the lowest ERA (2.90) among the Detroit starters.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The 1887 Wolverines finished the season with a record of 79–45.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] They outscored their opponents by more than 250 runs—969 to 714.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] They also led the National League in team batting average, runs scored and slugging.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] Louis Browns in the 1887 World Series, 10 games to 5.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] After the Wolverines won the National League pennant, owner Fred Stearns challenged the American Association champion St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines and the Browns would play "a series of contests for supremacy" of the baseball world.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] This early "world series" consisted of fifteen games – played in Pittsburgh, Brooklyn, New York, Philadelphia, Boston, Washington, Baltimore and Chicago, as well as Detroit and St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/1887-detroit-wolverines-season] The Wolverines claimed their eighth victory – and thus the championship – in the eleventh game.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He began playing organized baseball in Canada and Michigan and played one season of Major League Baseball as an infielder for the Indianapolis Hoosiers in 1884.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He was a manager of five major league clubs and several minor league clubs, including stints with the Indianapolis Hoosiers (1884–85), Detroit Wolverines (1885–1888), Kansas City Cowboys (1888–89), St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He led the 1887 Detroit Wolverines to the first professional sports championship for Detroit with a National League pennant and a victory over the St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He was also the business manager of the 1914 Indianapolis Hoosiers team that won the Federal League pennant, the first and only major league baseball championship for Indianapolis.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins was born in Brantford, Canada West, in 1858.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] His parents, John Harton Watkins and Eliza Jane (Tyler) Watkins, were immigrants to Canada from Wales and Ireland, respectively.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] His mother died in 1868, and he was thereafter raised by his maternal grandparents in Erin, Ontario.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins attended Upper Canada College in Toronto for one year, and he began playing organized baseball in 1876 as part of "the academy team" in Milton, Ontario, a suburb of Toronto.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He also held jobs as an apprentice for a manufacturer of novelty games and with a branch of the Ingles Corliss Engine Works.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In 1879, at age 21, Watkins moved to Port Huron, Michigan, where he lived for the next 40 years.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] From 1879 to 1880, Watkins played for the Maple Leafs of Guelph in Southwestern Ontario.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The Maple Leafs won the Canadian amateur championship while Watkins was a player.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In 1881 and/or 1882, he was a player-manager for the Atlantic Club of St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Thomas, Ontario (part of the London, Ontario metropolitan area).
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He led the Athletics to the Ontario provincial baseball championship in 1881.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins joined the Port Huron, Michigan baseball club late in the 1882 season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In 1883, he served as player-manager for the Port Huron club, playing at third base and leading the club to a Michigan State League championship.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In September 1883, Watkins was hired to take over as manager of the Bay City, Michigan club for the 1884 season at a salary of $2,000.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He led Bay City to a tie for first place in the Northwest League when the team disbanded in July 1884.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] On August 1, 1884, Watkins made his major league debut with the Indianapolis Hoosiers of the American Association.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins appeared in 34 games, 23 at third base, nine at second base and two at shortstop.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins also took over as the Hoosiers' manager, compiling a 4–18 record.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] On August 26, 1884, Watkins was hit on the head by a pitch from Gus Shallix, at Cincinnati.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Newspaper accounts indicate that he "hovered between life and death" for five days.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] It took two weeks for him to recover, and during that time, he lost 16 pounds.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins returned briefly as a player after the injury, but his performance was substantially diminished.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] On September 14, 1884, Watkins' error at second base let in most of Baltimore's runs in a 4–4 tie game.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He appeared in his final game as a player on October 13, 1884.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Newspaper stories published in 1912 in the *Indianapolis Star* and in 1937 in *The Sporting News* claimed that Watkins' hair turned prematurely white in 1884 due to the injury sustained when he was struck on the head.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In 1885, the Indianapolis club in the American Association disbanded.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Along with Ted Sullivan, Tom Loftus, and George Tebeau, Watkins helped organize the original Western League, a minor league baseball circuit based in the Midwestern United States.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] A new version of the Indianapolis Hoosiers was established in the Western League with Watkins as the manager.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] By mid-June, the Hoosiers were the dominant team in the Western League, compiling an .880 winning percentage.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] However, the league disbanded in mid-June, and a rush developed to sign the players on the Indianapolis roster, a line-up that included Sam Thompson, Deacon McGuire, Sam Crane, Jim Donnelly, Chub Collins, Mox McQuery, Gene Moriarty, and Dan Casey.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Sam Thompson later told the colorful story of the Hoosiers' acquisition by Detroit.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Detroit sent two representatives (Marsh and Maloney) to Indianapolis, principally to sign the Hoosiers' battery of Larry McKeon and Jim Keenan.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The Wolverines were outbid by the Cincinnati Reds for McKeon and Keenan but wound up with Watkins and the rest of the team's starting lineup.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The only catch was that a 10-day waiting period would allow other teams to outbid Detroit.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Marsh and Maloney promptly sent the players to Detroit and quartered them in a hotel there.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The next morning, the players were told that the team had arranged a fishing trip for them.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The players boarded the steamship *Annette* and enjoyed the first day and night of successful fishing.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] After three days, the players became suspicious, but the ship captain laughed when asked when they would return to Detroit.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] As the players became mutinous on the sixth day, the captain admitted he had been ordered to keep them "out at sea" for 10 days.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The players were only later presented with their accumulated mail which included scores of offers from other clubs.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] When Watkins took over as manager of the Detroit Wolverines in June 1885, the team had compiled a 7–31 record to that point in the season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] With the infusion of talent from Indianapolis, the team improved to 34–36 for the remainder of the 1885 season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] With the addition of the "Big Four", the Wolverines improved substantially, finishing in second place with an 85–38 record in 1886.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The 1887 season was the pinnacle in the history of the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The team was loaded with hitters, including six regulars who hit above .300: Sam Thompson (.372 and 166 RBIs in 127 games), Dan Brouthers (.338 and 101 RBIs in 123 games), Larry Twitchell (.333), Hardy Richardson (.328), Jack Rowe (.318) and Deacon White (.303).
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The pitching staff was led by "Pretzels" Getzien, a curveball specialist who compiled a 29–13 (.690) win–loss records and a 3.73 earned run average.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Outfielder Larry Twitchell also started 12 games as pitcher and compiled an 11–1 record.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The Wolverines won the National League pennant with a 79–45 record and then defeated the St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] During the 1888 season, the Wolverines fell to fifth place.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In late August 1888, the Detroit club fired, or accepted the resignation of, Watkins as their manager, and Robert Leadley was hired as "acting manager" in his place.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The Wolverines compiled a 49–44 record in their final year under Watkins.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] After parting ways with the Wolverines in late August 1888, Watkins was hired in early September 1888 as the manager of the Kansas City Cowboys of the American Association.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He led the club to an 8–17 record in the final month of the 1888 season and a 55–82 record in 1889.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In June 1890, Watkins was hired as the mid-season replacement manager for the St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Paul Apostles of the Western Association.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins had little success in turning the St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Paul club around, and in August 1890, *The Sporting Life* reported that Watkins had been forced to release players and cut salaries to reduce expenses, and that he was "running the St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Paul team economically according to instructions", though he hoped to have a stronger team in 1891.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The Apostles finished in last place in 1890 with a 37–84 record.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Flatley, a personal friend of Watkins, purchased the club and promptly signed Watkins to serve as the club's manager again in 1891.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] However, Flatley had sold the club by December 1890.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In June 1891, with the Apostles continuing to struggle financially and on the field, the club was sold and moved to Duluth, Minnesota.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Two months later, in August 1891, the club disbanded, and Watkins was left with financial responsibility for half of the Duluth team's unpaid player salaries.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In 1893, Watkins was hired as the manager of the St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Louis Browns (later renamed the Cardinals) of the National League.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Under owner Chris von der Ahe, the Browns had gone through five managers during the 1892 season, finishing in 11th place with a 56–94 (.373) record.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins remained the manager for the entire 1893 season and led the club to a 57-75 (.432) record and a 10th-place finish in 1893.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In 1894, Watkins was the manager of the Sioux City Cornhuskers in the newly formed Western League.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He led the Sioux City club to the first Western League pennant with a 74–52 record.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] By 1894, Watkins had won pennants as a manager in St.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] From 1895 through the early part of the 1898 season, Watkins was the manager of the Indianapolis Hoosiers/Indians in the Western League.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In 1898, Watkins was hired as the manager of the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Wasting the efforts of pitcher Jesse Tannehill (25–13 record and 2.95 ERA), the 1898 Pirates compiled a .258 team batting average (13 points below the league average) and finished in eighth place out of twelve teams with a 72–76 record.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] As he had been with other clubs, Watkins remained a strict disciplinarian as manager of the Pirates.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins also gained note while in Pittsburgh for his giving mandatory signs to each batter from the bench.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins described his sign system as follows: "I have only four, one telling the player to sacrifice, the second for the hit and run game, the third to hit the ball out, and the fourth to bunt.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] This completes the list, and they are as simple as can be.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins returned as the Pirates' manager in 1899 at an annual salary of $4,500, but he resigned in May 1899 after the team began the season with a 7–15 record.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins said at the time that he had other business to attend to, that he intended to quit baseball for good, and that he planned to return to his farm in Wadhams, Michigan: "I am going back to the farm to see the horses and dogs.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] I have wanted to give up base ball for some time past.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In November 1899, Watkins purchased the Indianapolis Hoosiers of the American League from John T.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Brush for "something like $10,000." Watkins also leased land on the east side of Indianapolis and announced plans to build a new baseball field there.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Speculation was immediate that Watkins was not a bona fide purchaser of the club and that he had "purchased" the club as a front man for Brush, who had been roundly criticized for his manipulations of the lineups of the two clubs (the Cincinnati Reds and Indianapolis Hoosiers) that he owned.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins also served as manager of the 1900 Indianapolis team, compiling a 71–64 record and finishing in third place.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] After American League president Ban Johnson converted the circuit into a major league, eliminating Indianapolis' spot in the league, Watkins was a leader of efforts in early 1901 to re-establish the American Association in competition with the American League.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In January 1901, he was named chairman of the new league.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The efforts to establish a new American Association were unsuccessful, and Watkins' Indianapolis club joined the Western Association for the 1901 season.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He sold the club in July 1901, and it was moved to Matthews, Indiana.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In late 1901, Watkins led renewed, and this time successful, efforts to re-establish a 20th-century version of the American Association with teams in Indianapolis, Louisville, Milwaukee, Kansas City, Columbus, Toledo and Minneapolis.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Official records cite John Grim as manager of the 1902 team, but Watkins' biographer Bill Lamb wrote that Watkins fully exercised duties now associated with a team manager.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Moreover, contemporaneous newspaper accounts in 1902 referred to Watkins as the team's manager.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The 1902 Indians compiled a 96–45 record and won the first American Association pennant.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins' 1903 team drew only 88,000 spectators, the lowest attendance in the American Association.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In November 1903, Watkins purchased the Minneapolis Millers of the American Association for $10,000.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins also served as the manager of the Minneapolis club during the 1904 and 1905 seasons.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] While managing the Millers, Watkins developed a reputation as a fierce competitor.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In December 1905, Watkins sold his ownership interest in the Minneapolis baseball club to Mike Kelley.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins returned to Indianapolis in 1906 as manager of the Indianapolis Indians of the American Association.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] *The Indianapolis Morning Star* reported that local baseball fans were "rejoicing", and that Watkins was "regarded as the most competent manager in the American Association." He had retained his half ownership interest in the Indianapolis club even while he was managing the Minneapolis team.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He was also president of the club from 1906 to 1912.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He stepped down as bench manager in May 1906, turning over responsibility of bench manager to Charlie Carr.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] As of January 1912, Watkins owned interests in baseball clubs in three different leagues: the Indianapolis Indians in the American Association, the Springfield, Ohio club in the Central League, and the Newark, Ohio club in the Ohio State League.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The Springfield and Newark clubs were both farm teams for the Indianapolis club.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In February 1914, Watkins was hired, at a salary reported to be $8,000, as the business manager for the Indianapolis Hoosiers team in the newly formed Federal League.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Upon his hiring, *The Sporting Life* opined: "William H.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The 1914 Hoosiers compiled an 88–65 record and won the first Federal League pennant, the first and only major league pennant in Indianapolis baseball history.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] However, in late March 1915, a deal was struck that resulted in the Indianapolis club being moved to Newark, New Jersey.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins did not follow the team to Newark.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] From 1920 to 1922, Watkins served as president of the Port Huron baseball club.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] In 1921, Watkins was one of the principal backers of the Port Huron club when it joined the Michigan–Ontario League.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins resigned the club's presidency in May 1922 in a letter stating that his business commitments prevented him from devoting the time needed for proper management of the club.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins was married in 1884 to Edna Buzzard.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins became a naturalized United States citizen in 1897.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] After retiring from baseball, Watkins lived in Port Huron, Michigan and worked as an executive at banks and land development and manufacturing companies.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He also served as president of the Port Huron Chamber of Commerce and helped found the city of Marysville, Michigan, serving as the first village president and chairing the committee that incorporated Marysville into a city.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He was elected justice of the peace in Marysville in 1933.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins died from diabetes in 1937 at age 79 in Port Huron.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] He was survived by his wife, Edna, and was buried at Lakeside Cemetery in Port Huron.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] The field used by both the Port Huron semipro and high school baseball teams was named Watkins Field in his honor, though it ceased being used in the early 1940s.
[src:bill-watkins-baseball/bill-watkins-baseball] Watkins was inducted into the Port Huron Sports Hall of Fame in 2008.
